title: For Sale/Trade:  300 WIN MAG
postcontent:
I'm considering selling my Thompson Center ProHunter Barrel in 300 WinMag.  It is blued and fluted and has only been fired 3 times and has never had a scope mounted on it.  It will also come with 8 boxes of Federal Premium 165 Barnes Triple Shock.  I'm only selling it to purchase other toys, so I'd have to get $500 out of the set.

The only 2 trades I'd consider are Kimber 1911 or 50 Beowulf Upper for an AR-15.  I really just want to sell it.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Virginian Dragoon 44 Mag 7 1/2 inch.
postcontent: Stainless single action imported from sweden in the mid 70's. Very well built gun with adjustable sights. Gun is engraved "Liberty Forever" on the bottom of the grip.

title: For Sale:  FS Tri Star Cobra Tactical
postcontent: Tri Star Cobra Tactical pump shotgun.  20" barrel fixed cyl. choke. Spring assisted pump. 5+1 mag capacity.  Mag extension is blocked per ATF importation rules.  This gun is unfired new in the box.  Face to face transfer in or near Cambridge Oh 43725.  Must be able to legally buy, own, and possess firearms.

The Forehand Arms Co. ( originally as Forehand and Wadsworth) was in business from the early 1870's until acquired by Hopkins & Allen sometime after the middle 1890's. They manufactured only (I believe ) low cost trade guns. There is probably no longer any serial number histroy available to determine exact age. In order to determine value the condition of the firearm has to be known. As you more than likely have read in my previous responses, refrain from shooting the decarbonized steel gun. Same was designed for low pressure loads of black-powder. title: For Sale:  Model 1816 Eli Whitney 1834  (Musket Has Been Cut Down)
postcontent:
This musket started its life as a US model 1816, 69 caliber smoothbore flintlock  musket. The Whitneyville Armory was awarded two contracts to produce these muskets between 1822 and 1841. Some collectors call it the Whitney model 1822, as it had some slight improvements over the standard 1816 model. Other then some early muskets having a "browned" barrel, I could never figure out just what else was different. The 1834 date on the lock plate is the year it was made. It is the second of the three types of lock plates used.

This musket  has been converted to percussion, probably in the 1840s or 50s, by what is called the "Belgian Alteration". The brass part you see on the lock, is what remains of the flash pan. The NG and 50 on the butt plate  May be a unit marking, as many of the model 1816s were given to the states as militia allotments. The initials JM on the barrel are credited to Justin Murphy, an inspector at the armory. Many of these muskets saw service in the early days of the civil war.

 At sometime, someone cut about a foot off the end of your barrel. It should be 42 inches long and have three bands holding it to the stock. After the civil war, all muzzle loaded firearms became obsolete, and there was thousands of them to be had. Many, were sold as cheap shotguns, and to make them easier to handle in the field, were shortened. Some were shortened by gunsmiths, and are nicely done, some were just sawed off. I actually saw one that was cut using a pipe cutter. It would be nice if it was not cut, it would be great if it was still an original flintlock. But all this is part of your muskets history, and our country's history as well. I'll bet there are not to many things you can buy today that will still be here in 175 years.
Payment is by US Postal Service money order only.

postcontent:
this is a 32 caliber rim fire, six shot revolver whose barrel swings up to allow the non-fluted cylinder to be removed for loading. It has a 5” octagon barrel and a spur trigger. It is referred to as a model Number 2 old model revolver and also the model number 2 Army. This is because earlier issues of this gun were used extensively as a personal side arm by officers and enlisted men during the Civil War. This gun has a blue finished and shows wear. However, the overall condition is very good and it functions very well. The grips are varnish rosewood with a square butt profile. The grips have an "x" notched into it on one side, possibly a marking from a kill in the war? A total of 77,155 of these were manufactured from 1861 to 1874. As a history note, General George Armstrong Custer was known to own a pair of these and ‘Wild Bill” Hitchcock, while Marshall of deadwood was carrying a model Army number 2 the night he was shot holding aces and eights in August of 1874

title: For Sale:  Nikon ProStaff 4-12x40 with Mil-Dot Reticle
postcontent:
As from the title, I have a flawless Nikon ProStaff 4-12x40 with Mil-Dot Reticle.  This is a great scope and I have thoroughly enjoyed it.  I have used it for (1) season for long shots across open fields.  The mil-dots have been a great advantage for hold-over indicators.  Put it this way, on my .308 Winchester scoped in at 100yd, I felt comfortable with 300yd shots.  With a simple ballistic calculator (I use Hornaday), I calculated 100, 200, 300, 400, and 500 yard MOA hold-overs for the specific bullet weight and ballistic coefficient.  I can help with this if you want me to.  The glass is super clear, turrets with 1/4" increments at 100yd, and with 12x magnification, I could count whiskers on the whitetails.


Typically the Nikon ProStaff has the standard duplex or BDC reticle.  I thought of getting the BDC reticle which has a generic hold-over indicator for multiple rifles but I wanted a more precise calculation and therefore, better tool to use in the field.  I purchased this scope for $175 plus $10 shipping.  Willing to sacrifice for $150 firm.

Oh, why am I selling.  The property I am going to hunt next has short, tight right-aways, with nothing over 75 yards.  I will be stepping down to a 2-7x32.
